D.3 Tabletop Quantum Gravity and Gravitational Entanglement

Theoretical Basis: If gravity is quantum, two massive objects should become entangled through their gravitational interaction, testing the quantum nature of the gravitational field.

Experimental Design: Two proposed experiments:

1. Torsion Pendulum Entanglement (proposed by Marletto and Vedral, 2017):
   ¬∑ Two 10‚Åª‚Åµ kg masses separated by 100 ¬µm
   ¬∑ Each in a superposition of two positions (¬±‚àÜx)
   ¬∑ Gravitational interaction creates phase shift:

```math
\phi = \frac{G m^2 t}{\hbar d} \left(\frac{1}{d - 2\Delta x} - \frac{1}{d + 2\Delta x}\right)
```

¬∑ Measure interference pattern to detect entanglement

1. Optomechanical Entanglement (proposed by Bose et al., 2017):
   ¬∑ Two 10‚Åª¬π‚Å¥ kg spheres in optical traps
   ¬∑ Cool to ground state (T ‚àº 10 ¬µK)
   ¬∑ Gravitational coupling constant:

```math
g = \frac{G m^2}{\hbar d^3} \sim 1 \ \text{Hz for } d = 100 \ \mu\text{m}
```

Experimental Challenges:

¬∑ Decoherence: Environmental noise limits coherence time
¬∑ Isolation: Need vibration isolation < 10‚Åª¬π‚Åµ m/‚àöHz
¬∑ Measurement: Single phonon sensitivity required

Current Status:

